# Approach 1: bitmasking
N.B. ```'1' & 0xf == 1```, this yields the same result as ```'1' - '0'```, but is still a neat trick to convert ASCII digits. That's a trick from the times when CPUs where a lot slower and it was cheaper to do ```and``` than ```sub```.

```cpp
    static bool isValidSudoku(const vector<vector<char>>& board) noexcept {
        array<int, 9> rows = {};
        array<int, 9> cols = {};
        array<int, 9> boxes = {};
        for (int r = 0; r < 9; ++r) {
            for (int c = 0; c < 9; ++c) {
                if (board[r][c] == '.') continue;
                const int mask = 1 << (board[r][c] & 0xf);
                // row
                if (rows[r] & mask) return false;
                rows[r] |= mask;
                // col
                if (cols[c] & mask) return false;
                cols[c] |= mask;
                // box    
                const int box = (r / 3)  * 3 + (c / 3);
                if (boxes[box] & mask) return false;
                boxes[box] |= mask;
            }
        }        
        return true;
    }
```

Maybe a quesion of taste, but we could also write this a bit more compact:

```cpp
    static bool isValidSudoku(const vector<vector<char>>& board) noexcept {
        array<int, 9> rows = {};
        array<int, 9> cols = {};
        array<int, 9> boxes = {};
        for (int r = 0; r < 9; ++r) {
            for (int c = 0; c < 9; ++c) {
                if (board[r][c] == '.') continue;
                const int mask = 1 << (board[r][c] & 0xf);
                const int box = (r / 3)  * 3 + (c / 3);
                if ((rows[r] & mask) || (cols[c] & mask) || (boxes[box] & mask))
                    return false;
                rows[r] |= mask;
                cols[c] |= mask;
                boxes[box] |= mask;
            }
        }        
        return true;
    }
```

Strictly speaking we could use ```array<short, 9>``` instead of ```array<int, 9>``` or maybe even pack everything into a ```bitset<81>```.

**Complexity Analysis**
The input size is fixed, hence this is $$O(1)$$ in both cases. Is this correct?
  * Time complexity: $$O(1)$$.
  * Space complexity: $$O(1)$$.

OTAH if we considered $$n$$ as the length of the board, i.e. 9 and assume it could grow then:
  * Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$ and
  * Space complexity: $$O(n)$$.

