```

***2. Using Unordered Maps (Hash Tables)***
```
    int singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {        
        unordered_map<int, int> um;
        for(int a: nums)
            um[a]++;
        for(auto it = um.begin(); it!=um.end(); it++){
            if(it->second==1)
                return it->first;
        }
        return 0;
    }
```

***3. Using XOR(^) bitwise operator to find unique number*** (Fastest)
Bitwise XOR Operator(^) has three properties: 
1. a^a = 0
2. 0^a = a
3. XOR is associative just like addition, multiplication, etc which means that -> a^b^c = a^(b^c) = (a^b)^c = (a^c)^b
So, when we XOR all the numbers in the list, all the numbers that occur 2 times become 0 as a^a = 0. At the end, we will be left with an expression like 0^n, where n is the only number occurring once. Using second property 0^a = a :-  0^n = n. Hence, we get the unique number.
```
    int singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {        

        // Using XOR property for Unique number
        int resultXOR = 0;                
        for(int a: nums)
            resultXOR ^= a;        
        return resultXOR;            
    }
```
