This problem only has three possible return values, root, p or q. The answer depends on whether p and q on the same subtree or not.

For those who find it hard to understand this solution, here is a little enlightenment: 
The last line of code only be executed one time in the end, we search left sub tree recursively try to find p or q whichever comes the first, if not we'll reach null and return null, same thing for the right subtree. and we compare the result in the last line of code.

    class Solution {
    public:
        TreeNode* lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode* root, TreeNode* p, TreeNode* q) {
            if (!root || root == p || root == q) return root;
            TreeNode* l = lowestCommonAncestor(root->left, p, q);
            TreeNode* r = lowestCommonAncestor(root->right, p, q);
            return l && r ? root : l ? l : r;
        }
    };

