solutions.content:
This specific problem can be solved in `O(n)` time (where `n` is the number of TreeNodes) using parent pointers. However a potential follow-up in an interview setting can be optimizing for `m` queries. A technique called Binary Lifting can be used for this - it requires us to build a DP array in `n*log(n)` time however once that is done, each LCA query can be done in `log(n)` time.

-----------

**Pre-requisites**

To use this technique we need the following information:

1. A unique identifier for each node (this will help with DP array computation)
2. The direct parent of each node
3. The depth/level/height of each node

First, let's assign a unique id for each node. I will declare two HashMaps `Map<Integer, TreeNode> map`  maps a unique id to a TreeNode and `Map<TreeNode, Integer> map2` is its inverse. We can then do a simple dfs based tree traversal and fill in labels.

```
class Solution {
    Map<Integer, TreeNode> map = new HashMap<>();
    Map<TreeNode, Integer> map2 = new HashMap<>();
	int id = 0;

    public TreeNode lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
        fillLabels(root);
        // TODO
    }

    // Labels each node from 0...n
    private void fillLabels(TreeNode root) {
        map2.put(root, id);
        map.put(id, root);
        id++;

        if(root.left != null) {
            fillLabels(root.left);
        }
        if(root.right != null) {
            fillLabels(root.right);
        }
    }
}
```

Once this is done, we can fill in the following by doing another dfs based traversal: 
1. The direct parent of each node - this will be stored in an array `parent[i]` that gives the direct parent of node i.
2. The level/height/depth of a node

```
class Solution {
    Map<Integer, TreeNode> map = new HashMap<>();
    Map<TreeNode, Integer> map2 = new HashMap<>();

    Map<Integer, Integer> levels = new HashMap<>();
    int id = 0;
    int[] parent;

    public TreeNode lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
        fillLabels(root);

        parent = new int[map.size()];
        parent[0] = -1;
        levels.put(0, 0);
        fillLevelsAndParent(root);
		// TODO
    }

    // Record level information and fill parent array
    private void fillLevelsAndParent(TreeNode root) {
        int rootVal = map2.get(root);
        int nextLevel = levels.get(rootVal) + 1;

        if(root.left != null) {
            int leftVal = map2.get(root.left);
            parent[leftVal] = rootVal;
            levels.put(leftVal, nextLevel);
            fillLevelsAndParent(root.left);
        }

        if(root.right != null) {
            int rightVal = map2.get(root.right);
            parent[rightVal] = rootVal;
            levels.put(rightVal, nextLevel);
            fillLevelsAndParent(root.right);
        }
    }

    // Labels each node from 0...n
    private void fillLabels(TreeNode root) { ... }
```

-----

**Kth ancestor of a TreeNode**

Our next objective is to find the Kth ancestor of a TreeNode - this is a separate problem on Leetcode (LC-1483) linked [here](https://leetcode.com/problems/kth-ancestor-of-a-tree-node/). 

Similar to the LCA problem, you can solve this in `O(n)` if there is just one query however if there are `m` queries, you need to do this in a better way. The idea is using a DP table to pre-compute ancestors of a node. There are a couple of different ways to approach this problem.

**Method 1:** If the number of nodes are small you can define a function `f(i, j)` that returns the `ith` ancestor of a node with id `j`. The recurrence relation is as follows:

```
f(i, j) = -1 // if parent[j] = -1
f(i, j) = parent[j] // if i == 1
f(i, j) = f(i-1, parent[j]) // otherwise
```

Using this recurrence we can construct a DP array in `O(n^2)` time and space. Once constructed, queries are extremely fast and can be done in constant time. However if the number of nodes are large and `n^2` is too much, this will not work - hence we use method 2.

**Method 2:**  Here we re-define our function as follows: Define `f(i, j)` as a function that returns the `2^jth` parent of node `i`. The recurrence relation is as follows:

```
f(j, i) = parent[i] // if j = 0
f(j, i) = f(j-1, f(j-1, i)) // otherwise (assuming f(j-1, i) is not -1)
```

Now since there exist only `n` nodes, we can make at most `n` jumps. Since we are storing ancestors in powers of 2, we can make at most `log(n)` jumps in the worst case.

The dp array can be initialized as follows:

```
    private void initializeCache() {
        int n = parent.length;
        int logN =  (int) (Math.log(n)/Math.log(2))+1;
        dp =  new int[logN][n];

        for(int i = 0; i<logN; i++) {
            for(int j = 0; j<n; j++) {
                if(i == 0)
                    dp[i][j] = parent[j];
                else if(dp[i-1][j] == -1)
                    dp[i][j] = -1;
                else
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][dp[i-1][j]];
            }
        }
    }
```

The idea here is to use the binary value of `k` to make jumps and get the `kth` ancestor. Let's say you want to get the 13th ancestor of a node `x`. Any number can be represented in binary form so 13 is: `1101`. This is the equivalent of the following: 

13 = `1* 2^3 + 1* 2^2 + 0* 2^1 + 1* 2^0`

So to find the 13th ancestor of k, we can do the following: 
- get the `2^0th` ancestor of `k` stored in `dp[0][k]` let's call this `k1`
- get the `2^2th` ancestor of `k1` stored in `dp[2][k1]` let's call this `k2`
-  get the `3^3th` ancestor of `k2` stored in `dp[3][k2]` let's call this `k3`

And we are done.

```
    private int kthAncestor(int node, int k) {
        String binaryString = Integer.toBinaryString(k);
        int currentNode = node;
        int powerOfTwo = 0;

        for(int i = binaryString.length()-1; i>=0; i--) {
            if(binaryString.charAt(i) == '1')
                currentNode = dp[powerOfTwo][currentNode];
            if(currentNode == -1)
                return -1;
            powerOfTwo++;
        }
        return currentNode;
    }
```

---------

**Getting the LCA of two Nodes**

Finally we have everything we need to get the LCA.

**Step 1:** Ensure both nodes are on the same level. We can do this in `log(n)` time - get the height/depth of the two nodes. Find the levelDifference between the 2. Then use the `kthAncestor(node, levelDifference)` to move the lower node to the same level.

```
    private void normalizeLevels(int p, int q) {
        if(levels.get(p) == levels.get(q)) {
            node1 = p;
            node2 = q;
            return;
        }
        if(levels.get(p) < levels.get(q)) {
            normalizeLevels(q, p);
            return;
        }

        int levelDifference = levels.get(p) - levels.get(q);
        p = kthAncestor(p, levelDifference);
        node1 = p;
        node2 = q;
    }
```

The end result of this function is that two nodes with ids `node1` and `node2` are on the same level of the tree. This has been done in `log(n)` time.

**Step 2:** Find the LCA of `node1` and `node2`. The challenge is doing this in log(n) complexity. To do this we need to think about what happens when we make a jump.

Let's say I make an arbitrary size jump and update the values the values of `node1` and `node2` accordingly. Assuming the LCA is `nodeX`, if I made a jump directly to `nodeX` or a jump greater than that to something above `nodeX`, then `node1 == node2`. However if I made a smaller jump then `node1 != node2`.

The idea is to make the largest jumps possible such that `node1 != node2` in a loop until we cannot make any more jumps.

- The largest jump posible is a jump of size `n` which is `2^(log(n))`
	-  If we overshoot (which we will), dont make the jump.
	-  Otherwise make the jump
- Next make a jump of size `2^(log(n)-1)`
	- If we overshoot, do not make the jump. Else make the jump.
- Keep doing this until `2^0`

In the end the direct parent of any of the nodes is the LCA.

```
    private void getLca() {
        if(node1 == node2)
            return;
        int n = map.size();
        int start = (int) (Math.log(n)/Math.log(2));

        for(int i = start; i>=0; i--) {
            int pNode1 = kthAncestor(node1, i);
            int pNode2 = kthAncestor(node2, i);

            if(pNode1 == pNode2) {
                continue;           // do not do the jump
            } else {                // do the jump
                node1 = pNode1;
                node2 = pNode2;
            }
        }
    }
```

And we are done!

------------

**Full code**

Putting it all together we have the following solution:

- Time Complexity: n* log(n) to build the DP array and log(n) for each query
- Spacr Complxity: n* log(n) for the DP array

Code:

```
class Solution {
    Map<Integer, TreeNode> map = new HashMap<>();
    Map<TreeNode, Integer> map2 = new HashMap<>();

    Map<Integer, Integer> levels = new HashMap<>();
    int id = 0;
    int[] parent;
    int[][] dp;

    int node1;
    int node2;

    public TreeNode lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
        fillLabels(root);

        parent = new int[map.size()];
        parent[0] = -1;
        levels.put(0, 0);
        fillLevelsAndParent(root);

        initializeCache();        
        normalizeLevels(map2.get(p), map2.get(q));
        getLca();

        if(node1 == node2)
            return map.get(node1);
        else
            return map.get(parent[node1]);
    }

    private void getLca() {
        if(node1 == node2)
            return;
        int n = map.size();
        int start = (int) (Math.log(n)/Math.log(2));

        for(int i = start; i>=0; i--) {
            int pNode1 = kthAncestor(node1, i);
            int pNode2 = kthAncestor(node2, i);

            if(pNode1 == pNode2) {
                continue;           // do not do the jump
            } else {                // do the jump
                node1 = pNode1;
                node2 = pNode2;
            }
        }
    }

    private void normalizeLevels(int p, int q) {
        if(levels.get(p) == levels.get(q)) {
            node1 = p;
            node2 = q;
            return;
        }
        if(levels.get(p) < levels.get(q)) {
            normalizeLevels(q, p);
            return;
        }

        int levelDifference = levels.get(p) - levels.get(q);
        p = kthAncestor(p, levelDifference);
        node1 = p;
        node2 = q;
    }

    private int kthAncestor(int node, int k) {
        String binaryString = Integer.toBinaryString(k);
        int currentNode = node;
        int powerOfTwo = 0;

        for(int i = binaryString.length()-1; i>=0; i--) {
            if(binaryString.charAt(i) == '1')
                currentNode = dp[powerOfTwo][currentNode];
            if(currentNode == -1)
                return -1;
            powerOfTwo++;
        }
        return currentNode;
    }

    /*
        Let f(i, j) return 2^ith ancestor of node j
            f(i, j) = parent[j]         // if i = 0
            f(i, j) = f(i-1, f(i-1, j)) // otherwise (assuming f(i-1, j) != -1)
    */
    private void initializeCache() {
        int n = parent.length;
        int logN =  (int) (Math.log(n)/Math.log(2))+1;
        dp =  new int[logN][n];

        for(int i = 0; i<logN; i++) {
            for(int j = 0; j<n; j++) {
                if(i == 0)
                    dp[i][j] = parent[j];
                else if(dp[i-1][j] == -1)
                    dp[i][j] = -1;
                else
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][dp[i-1][j]];
            }
        }
    }

    // Record level information and fill parent array
    private void fillLevelsAndParent(TreeNode root) {
        int rootVal = map2.get(root);
        int nextLevel = levels.get(rootVal) + 1;

        if(root.left != null) {
            int leftVal = map2.get(root.left);
            parent[leftVal] = rootVal;
            levels.put(leftVal, nextLevel);
            fillLevelsAndParent(root.left);
        }

        if(root.right != null) {
            int rightVal = map2.get(root.right);
            parent[rightVal] = rootVal;
            levels.put(rightVal, nextLevel);
            fillLevelsAndParent(root.right);
        }
    }

    // Labels each node from 0...n
    private void fillLabels(TreeNode root) {
        map2.put(root, id);
        map.put(id, root);
        id++;

        if(root.left != null) {
            fillLabels(root.left);
        }
        if(root.right != null) {
            fillLabels(root.right);
        }
    }
}
```

