solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We need to return in bottom-up manner to avoid searching the same subtree multiple times

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
At each root we make recursive calls to the left and right subtree and return on the basis of follwoing criteria
Return root if its equal to p or q
Return p if only p is present
Return q if only q is present
Return LCA if already found
Return NULL if none are present
Return root if LST and RST each have p/q 
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(number of nodes)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(height) due to recursion
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * struct TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode *left;
 *     TreeNode *right;
 *     TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(NULL), right(NULL) {}
 * };
 */
class Solution {
public:
    TreeNode* lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode* root, TreeNode* p, TreeNode* q) {
        if(!root) return nullptr;
        if(root->val == p->val || root->val == q->val) return root;

        TreeNode* lst = lowestCommonAncestor(root->left, p, q);
        TreeNode* rst = lowestCommonAncestor(root->right, p, q);
        if(!lst) return rst; //always return the non NULL value
        if(!rst) return lst; // if both are NULL we return NULL only

        return root;
    }
};
```

