For different indices (i, j), the concatenation of A = words[i] and B = words[j] is palindrome if and only if
(i) B + A is aplindrome: A_suf[::-1] == B, A_pre is palindrome
(ii) A + B is palindrome: A_pre[::-1] == B, A_suf is palindrome
where A_pre = A[:k], A_suf = A[k:] for k equals one of 0, 1, ..., len(A). 

Let n = len(words), m be the maximal length of these words.

Solution 1 with O(n^2 m) time and O(1) space:
```
    def palindromePairs(self, words):
        def is_palindrome_pair(A, B):
            lA, lB = len(A), len(B)
            i, j = 0, lA + lB - 1
            while i < j:
                s_i = A[i] if i < lA else B[i-lA]
                s_j = A[j] if j < lA else B[j-lA]
                if s_i != s_j:
                    return False
                i, j = i + 1, j - 1
            return True

        valid_pals = []
        n = len(words)
        for i in range(n - 1):
            for j in range(i + 1, n):
                if is_palindrome_pair(words[i], words[j]):
                    valid_pals.append([i, j])
                if is_palindrome_pair(words[j], words[i]):
                    valid_pals.append([j, i])
        return valid_pals
```

Solution 2 with O(n * m^2) time and O(n * m) space:
For each word A = words[i], use a dictionary to search B = words[j].
```
    def palindromePairs(self, words):
        def is_palindrome(check):
            return check == check[::-1]

        valid_pals = []
        words = {word: i for i, word in enumerate(words)}
        for word in words:
            m = len(word)
            for k in range(m+1):
                prefix = word[:k]
                suffix = word[k:]
                if is_palindrome(prefix):
                    back = suffix[::-1]
                    if back in words and words[back] != words[word]:
                        valid_pals.append([words[back],  words[word]])
                if k != m and is_palindrome(suffix): # k!= m is added to avoid considering A == B[::-1]  twice
                    back = prefix[::-1]
                    if back in words and words[back] != words[word]:
                        valid_pals.append([words[word], words[back]])
        return valid_pals
```

Solution 3 with O(n * m^2) time and O(n * m) space:
For each word A = words[i], use a trie to search B = words[j]. 
This method can be modified a little bit to work for follow up questions: 
n is very large, duplicated words exist.

