***1) Brute Force:(TLE)***

```
Brute force approach is quite straightforward,
consider every pair of strings and check if the string formed is palindrome or not.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Time Complexity : O(N^2 * M),
where N -- the number of words.
M -- maximum length of word that can be formed by concatenation of two words. 
```
```---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------```
**C++**
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool check(string a)
    {
        int i=0,j=a.length()-1;
        while(i<=j)
        {
            if(a[i]!=a[j])
                return false;
            i++;
            j--;
        }
        return true;
    }
    vector<vector<int>> palindromePairs(vector<string>& words) 
    {
        vector<vector<int>> res;
        for(int i=0;i<words.size();i++)
        {
            for(int j=0;j<words.size();j++)
            {
                if(i!=j)
                {
                    if(check(words[i]+words[j]))
                        res.push_back({i,j});
                }
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

```---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------```

***2)Optimization(Accepted):***
```
1) First of all, as in the output we need to return indices corresponding to the possible candidates, 
so it is very clear that we need to have mapping between word and its index.

2 Now, Each string can be divided at particular index into two substrings,first is prefix string and second is suffix string,
we first check whether prefix string is a palindrome and if so then there is a possibility that by using this prefix string,we can form a new palindrome.

So, to check whether the palindrome can be formed using prefix string,we need to check whether the reverse of suffix string is present in the map or not.
And same goes for the case when we try suffix string as the possible candidate for palindrome.

3) If for prefix string , the reverse suffix string's index is different as of the current string, then we are sure that we found a pair of palindromic strings.

4) If for suffix string , the reverse prefix string's index is different as of the current string, then we are sure that we found another pair of palindromic strings.
```
```
# Time Complexity: O(N * M^2),
# N -- number of words,
# M -- Average length of words(Worst Case).
```

```---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------```

**C++(USING MAPS)**
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPalindrome(string &str)
    {
        int i=0;
        int j=str.length()-1;
        while(i<=j)
        {
            if(str[i]!=str[j])
                return false;
            i++,j--;
        }
        return true;
    }
    vector<vector<int>> palindromePairs(vector<string>& words) {
        vector<vector<int>> res;
        if(words.size()<2)
            return res;
        unordered_map<string,int> mp;
        for(int i=0;i<words.size();i++)
            mp[words[i]] = i;

        for(int i=0;i<words.size();i++)
        {
            for(int j=0;j<=words[i].length();j++)
            {
                string prefixString = words[i].substr(0,j);
                string suffixString = words[i].substr(j);

                if(isPalindrome(prefixString))
                {
                    string reverseString = suffixString;
                    reverse(reverseString.begin(),reverseString.end());
                    if(mp.count(reverseString) and mp[reverseString]!=i)
                    {
                        res.push_back({mp[reverseString],i});
                    }
                }

                if(isPalindrome(suffixString))
                {
                    string reverseString = prefixString;
                    reverse(reverseString.begin(),reverseString.end());
                    if(mp.count(reverseString) and mp[reverseString]!=i and !suffixString.empty())
                    {
                        res.push_back({i,mp[reverseString]});
                    }
                }

            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

