solutions.content:
- A lot of people are frustated with TLE errors (especially for last 2 test cases 135th and 136th)
- Consistent TLEs made me doubt if my Trie approach was even worth doing
- But it is indeed okay if some care is taken
- Added word in Trie is referred to as a stored word, the words that are then searched for in the trie are referred to as search key.

#### Basic approach 
- Reverse all words and insert in a trie.
- Then search with normal (unreversed) words. If a match is made, then that means the reverse of one word and normal order of other word are equal i.e the concatenation can form a palindrome. Add this pair in final answer. (For order, the search key (i.e unreversed word) will come first and the existing key stored in trie will come later because a search key i - "abcd" matching j - "abcd" stored in trie means  that j was "dcba" and was reversed and then stored so i + j i.e abcd + dcba are forming palindrome ).

### Special cases
- It is not difficult to observe that a palindrome can be formed by not just pairs like "abcd" & "dcba", but by other cases too. "abcd**txt**" & "dcba" are also forming palindrome. This means that "dcba" will be reversed and stored as "abcd" .The search key "abcd**txt**" will match with this stored word only upto some length. So we need to check at all terminal nodes (i.e the nodes where a word is ending:  "d" for "abcd" in this case )that the remainng part of the search key "**txt**" might itself be a palindrome so we need to consider this pair also.
- By similar logic, we look at other case. "abcd" & "**txt**dcba" also form a palindrome. "txtdcba" will be reversed and stored as "abcd**txt**". In this case the search key "abcd" will totatlly match with word in trie, but the node might not be a terminal node. So at every node we need to know that even if we are stopping the comparison, the word in the trie might have palindromes ahead. For instance the search key i - "abcd" might exhaust at "abcd" in trie and we might think that since d is not terminal, no pair has been found. But "abcd" in trie might lead to j - "abcd**txt**" & k -"abcd**fbhbf**". Both of which are valid pairs with our search key. So we need to store about j & k at node "d" itself, so that once we stop comparsion, we can just use values i,j & i,k from node "d" only.
- What the previous two points mean is that while adding in trie, we need to check at each inserted node if remaining string is a palindrom and store the index in curent node itself if remaining string is a palindrome. Similarly, while searching also, if we see a terminal node for a word, then we can check if our remaining search key is a palindrome or not and add that pair.

#### Storage Structure
- Each node should store whether it is terminal or not (like all tries).
- If terminal, then index(id) of word ending at this node needs to be stored
- Also an array(list) of all indexes(id's) of words that follow and have remaining string as palindrome needs to be stored at current node.

### Avoiding TLE

- Basic one - Don't use recursion for inserting/searching in Trie, use iteration to avoid function calls.
- Dont actually reverse the strings to insert, since that itself will be time consuming. Just start from length -1 and go to 0 as we insert.
- Dont pass by value, as it leads to copying of values, pass references instead.

Simple code but with TLE - **Dont waste time reading**

```
bool isPalFun(string word)
{
    int n = word.length();
    for(int i = 0; i<n/2; i++)
    {
        if(word[i] != word[n-1-i])
            return false;
    }
    return true;
};

class Node{
    public:
    bool isTerminal;
    int terminalIndex;
    vector<int> * Pals;
    Node ** children;

    Node()
    {
        isTerminal = false;
        Pals = new vector<int>();

        children = new Node*[26];
        for(int i = 0; i<26; i++)
            children[i] = NULL;
    }
};
class Solution {
    Node* root;
public:
    Solution()
    {
        root = new Node();
    }
    void insert(Node *root, string word, int index)
    {
        if(word.length() == 0)
        {
            root->terminalIndex = index;
            root->isTerminal = true;
            return;
        }

        if(isPalFun(word))  // while inserting, check for each node
        {
            root->Pals->push_back(index);
        }

        if(root->children[word[0]-'a'] == NULL)
            root->children[word[0] - 'a'] = new Node();

        insert(root->children[word[0] - 'a'], word.substr(1),index);
    }
    vector<vector<int>> search(Node * root, string word, int index)
    {
        if(root == NULL)
        {
           vector<vector<int>> ans;
            return ans;
        }
        if(word.length() == 0)
        {
           vector<vector<int>> ans;
            if(root->isTerminal)
            {
                if(root->terminalIndex != index)
                {
                    vector<int> v{index, root->terminalIndex};
                    ans.push_back(v);
                }
            }

            for(int p : *(root->Pals))
            {
                if(p != index)
                {
                    vector<int> v{index, p};
                    ans.push_back(v);
                }
            }

            return ans;
        }

        vector<vector<int>> smallAns = search(root->children[word[0] - 'a'], word.substr(1), index);

        if(root->isTerminal)
        {
            if(isPalFun(word))
            {
               vector<int> v{index, root->terminalIndex};
                smallAns.push_back(v); 
            }
        }

        return smallAns;
    }
    vector<vector<int>> palindromePairs(vector<string>& words) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        for(int i = 0; i<words.size(); i++)
        {
            string rev = words[i];
            reverse(rev.begin(), rev.end());
            insert(root, rev, i);
        }
        for(int i = 0; i<words.size(); i++)
        {
            auto a = search(root, words[i], i);
            for(int j = 0; j<a.size(); j++)
                ans.push_back(a[j]);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
``` 
### Accepted code without TLE

```
bool isPal(string &s,int i, int j)
{
    while(j > i)
    {
        if(s[i++] != s[j--])
            return false;
    }
    return true;
}

class Node{
public:
    Node ** children;
    int index;
    vector<int> pals;  // for storing indexes of those words that have remaining substring as palindrome after this node.
    Node()
    {
        children = new Node*[26];
        for(int i = 0; i<26; i++)
            children[i] = NULL;

        index = -1;
    }
};

class Solution {
    Node* root;
public:
    Solution()
    {
        root = new Node();
    }
    vector<vector<int>> palindromePairs(vector<string>& words) {
        int n = words.size();

        // ADD reverse of all words into trie
        for(int i = 0; i<n; i++)
        {
            Node* cur = root;
            for(int j = words[i].length() -1; j >= 0; j--)  // j starts from end and goes to 0 bcz reverse string added.
            {
                if(!(cur->children[words[i][j] - 'a']))  // declare if child node doesn't exist
                    cur->children[words[i][j] - 'a'] = new Node();

                if(isPal(words[i],0,j))     // store index in current node if remaining string is a palindrome
                    cur->pals.push_back(i);

                cur = cur->children[words[i][j] - 'a'];
            }

            cur->index = i;         // mark the node is terminal by changing index from -1 to actual index
            cur->pals.push_back(i);
        }

        vector<vector<int>> ans;

        // now search for all words
        for(int i = 0; i<n; i++)
        {
            Node *cur = root;
            for(int j = 0; j< words[i].length; j++)
            {
                if(cur->index != -1)   // we are at terminal node
                    if(cur->index != i)   // bcz we dont want i,i pair to get added
                        if(isPal(words[i], j, words[i].length()-1))  // means stored word has ended, and the remainng search key is a palindrome
                            ans.push_back({i, cur->index});

				cur = cur->children[words[i][j] - 'a'];

				if(cur == NULL)
					break;
            }

            if(cur != NULL)
			 {
				for(int e : cur->pals)  // the search key has ended, now simply add word indexes that have some palidrome string remaining ahead of this node.
				{
					if(i != e)
						ans.push_back({i, e});
				}
			}
        return ans;
    }
};
```

