This solution is directly inspired by [214. Shortest Palindrome](https://leetcode.com/problems/shortest-palindrome/) and the impressive [solution](https://leetcode.com/problems/shortest-palindrome/discuss/60113/) by @myfavcat123.

As long as we can find the shortest complement required to make the original string a palindrome by KMP algorihtm in linear time, why can't we find all those complements in the same way?

Note that for any concatenation of two strings that form a palindrome, at least one of them can be seen as the other's *complement*.

Let's take two examples:
Case 1 - `ssl` + `lllss`, in which `ssl` can be seen as `lllss`'s complement, and **NOT** vice versa.
Case 2 - `abc` + `cba`, in which `abc` can be seen as `cba`'s complement, and vice versa.

It's obvious that the complement is either placed before or after the *primary* string. So we can use the aforementioned KMP algorithm to get all the complements in two directions (forward / backward). And then we check whether those complements exist in the given words. If so, they'll form a palindrome.

A few caveats concerning the procedure:
1. The `substring` method costs O(k) (k is the length of string) time, which is the bottleneck raising the entire time complexity to O(n * k^2) (n is the total of strings).
2. To avoid duplicates, use `HashSet` and convert it to a list lastly.

```
class Solution {
    public List<List<Integer>> palindromePairs(String[] words) {
        Map<String, Integer> wordMap = new HashMap<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < words.length; i++) {
            wordMap.put(words[i], i);
        }

        Set<List<Integer>> res = new HashSet<>();

        for (int i = 0; i < words.length; i++) {
            List<List<String>> targets = getPairStrs(words[i]);
            for (int j = 0; j < targets.size(); j++) {
                for (String target : targets.get(j)) {
                    Integer idx = wordMap.get(target);
                    if (idx != null && idx != i) {
                        res.add(j == 0 ? List.of(i, idx) : List.of(idx, i));
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return List.copyOf(res);
    }

    private List<List<String>> getPairStrs(String str) {
        String reverse = new StringBuilder(str).reverse().toString();
        String[] concats = {reverse + "*" + str, str + "*" + reverse};

        int[][] kmpTables = {getKmpTable(concats[0]), getKmpTable(concats[1])};

        // pairStrs stores strings that can be concatenated with 'str' and form a palindrome
        // which are either placed before or after the original 'str'
        List<List<String>> pairStrs = List.of(new ArrayList(), new ArrayList());
        for (int i = 0; i < concats.length; i++) {
            // i == 0 -> Forward concatenation, in which the complement comes after 'str'
            // i == 1 -> Backward concatenation, in which the complement comes before 'str'
            int curr = kmpTables[i][concats[i].length()];

            while (curr >= 0) {
                pairStrs.get(i).add(
                    i == 0 ? reverse.substring(curr): reverse.substring(0, reverse.length() - curr)
                );
                curr = kmpTables[i][curr];
            }
        }

        return pairStrs;
    }

    private int[] getKmpTable(String str) {
        int[] table = new int[str.length() + 1];
        table[0] = -1;

        for (int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {
            int curr = table[i];
            while (curr >= 0 && str.charAt(curr) != str.charAt(i)) curr = table[curr];
            table[i + 1] = curr + 1;
        }

        return table;
    }
}
