Oct. 20, 2020
336. Palindrome Pairs

**Introduction**
It is hard for me to prepare for Nov. 5, 2020 Google phone screen in 4 weeks, so I asked the advice from a friend. I got this tip. 

What I do is to look up Google using keyword "Leetcode pattern Google", and go to "Leetcode Patterns - Sean Prashad", and go over all 34 hard level algorithms, and then go over all 97 medium level algorithms.  I came cross this hard level algorithm.

**Code study**
There are more than two ideas to solve, one is to use hashMap, and second one is to use trie. I like to practice it using hashMap first. 

**Case study**
Input: words = ["bat","tab","cat"]
Output: [[0,1],[1,0]]

First put all reversed words into dictionary, so "bat"'s reversed word "tab" is added to the hashMap, next one is "bat", last one is "tac". The reversed hashMap has three words: {"tab", "bat","tac"); 

Next is to go over each word, and then try to break the word into two pieces. One of two is a palindrome, and the other one can be find in the reversed words's hashMap. 

**Time complexity**
Time is to put all reversed words into hashMap is O(N * M), N is total number of words, M is average length of word. 
Second step is to break into two pieces. The time complexity is O(M * M), first part is M choices, M is average length of word, second part M is time to calculate palindrome. 
In summary, it should be O(N * M + M * M). 

```
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Text;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

namespace _336_palindromic_pairs
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
        }

        /// <summary>
        /// Palindromic - 336
        /// Study code
        /// https://leetcode.com/problems/palindrome-pairs/discuss/309105/C-dictionary-for-reversedWord-cut-each-word-to-get-left-part-and-right-part
        /// </summary>
        /// <param name="words"></param>
        /// <returns></returns>
        public IList<IList<int>> PalindromePairs(string[] words)
        {
            var result = new List<IList<int>>();

            // the hashmap to contain reversed word
            var reversedMap = new Dictionary<string, int>();

            for (int i = 0; i < words.Length; i++)
            {
                var word = words[i];

                if (word == "")
                {
                    continue;
                }

                var reverse = new string(word.Reverse().ToArray());
                reversedMap[reverse] = i;
            }

            for (int i = 0; i < words.Length; i++)
            {
                var word = words[i];               

                if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(word))
                {
                    for (int j = 0; j < words.Length; j++)
                    {
                        if (i == j)
                        {
                            continue;
                        }

                        if (IsPalindrome(words[j]))
                        {
                            result.Add(new List<int> { i, j });
                            result.Add(new List<int> { j, i });
                        }
                    }
                }
                else
                {
                    for (int j = 0; j < word.Length; j++)
                    {
                        var prefix = word.Substring(0, j);
                        var suffix = word.Substring(j);

                        // prefix + suffix + reverse(prefix) -> suffix is palindrome
                        if (reversedMap.ContainsKey(prefix) && reversedMap[prefix] != i && IsPalindrome(suffix))
                        {
                            result.Add(new List<int> { i, reversedMap[prefix] });
                        }

                        // reverse(suffix) + prefix + suffix -> prefix is palindrom
                        if (reversedMap.ContainsKey(suffix) && reversedMap[suffix] != i && IsPalindrome(prefix))
                        {
                            result.Add(new List<int> { reversedMap[suffix], i });
                        }
                    }
                }
            }

            return result;
        }

        private bool IsPalindrome(string s)
        {
            var start = 0;
            var end = s.Length - 1;

            while (start < end)
            {
                if (s[start] != s[end])
                {
                    return false;
                }

                start++;
                end--;
            }

            return true;
        }
    }
}
